[2026-03-03T05:52:50.641Z] event=response.thinking data={"content_index":0,"sequence_number":147,"text":"\nThe user is asking to count something per month based on \"first_transaction_date\". They've selected the SalesSemantic tool to use.\n\nLet me think about this question:\n1. The user wants counts aggregated by month\n2. They specifically mention \"first_transaction_date\" as the date field to use\n3. However, looking at the SalesSemantic tool description, I don't see a column called \"first_transaction_date\" in the TBL_SALES table\n\nThe available date columns in SalesSemantic are:\n- TRANSACTION_DATE (date of transaction)\n- CREATED_AT (timestamp of record creation)\n\nThere's no \"first_transaction_date\" column listed. This could mean:\n1. The user is mistaken about the column name\n2. They want me to derive \"first transaction date\" from TRANSACTION_DATE\n3. They want a count of transactions per month using TRANSACTION_DATE\n\nGiven the context, the most reasonable interpretation is that the user wants to count transactions per month based on TRANSACTION_DATE. However, \"first_transaction_date\" suggests they might want something more specific - like the first transaction date per customer.\n\nSince the question is somewhat ambiguous about:\n- What to count (number of sales? number of customers?)\n- Whether \"first_transaction_date\" is a column name or a concept they want derived\n\nHowever, according to the clarification rules, I should NOT ask for clarification about terminologies when SQL processing tools are available. The term \"count\" with \"per month\" is clear enough - they want monthly aggregated counts. I should make a reasonable assumption and proceed.\n\nI'll interpret this as: count the number of sales transactions per month based on the TRANSACTION_DATE field over the entire available time period.\n"}
